[{"instruction": "Explain the difference between git merge and git rebase and when to use each. Include concrete commands, examples of common workflows (e.g., feature branch maintenance, preparing a PR), pros and cons, conflict handling, and recommended team policies.", "response": "git merge and git rebase both integrate commits from one branch into another, but they do so differently and are suited to different situations.\n\nWhat git merge does:\n- Combines histories by creating a merge commit (unless a fast-forward is possible). The merge commit preserves the topology of branches.\n- Command example (merge feature into main):\n  git checkout main\n  git merge feature-branch\n- Variants: --no-ff forces a merge commit; --squash produces one squashed commit (no merge commit).\n- Pros: preserves true historical context, safe for public/shared branches, non-destructive.\n- Cons: can create a cluttered graph with many merge commits if branches are long-lived.\n\nWhat git rebase does:\n- Reapplies commits from your branch onto another branch tip, rewriting history so commits appear as if created after the target branch.\n- Command example (move feature on top of main):\n  git checkout feature-branch\n  git rebase main\n- Interactive rebase to clean up commits before sharing:\n  git rebase -i main    # squash, reorder, fixup commits\n- After rebasing a branch that was pushed, force-push is required:\n  git push --force-with-lease\n- Pros: produces a linear, cleaner history; good for local cleanup.\n- Cons: rewrites commit hashes (dangerous for commits shared with others); can make blame/history harder if used on public commits.\n\nConflict handling (both approaches):\n- When conflicts occur, Git will pause and mark conflicts. Resolve files, then:\n  git add <file>\n  git merge --continue    # after merge conflict resolution\n  git rebase --continue    # after rebase conflict resolution\n- If rebase goes wrong, you can abort: git rebase --abort. For merge: git merge --abort.\n\nWhen to use which (practical guidance):\n- Use merge when integrating long-lived branches (release, develop) or when you want an explicit history of integration points. Merge is the safe default for public branches.\n- Use rebase for local feature-branch maintenance: keep your branch up-to-date with main, clean up commits with git rebase -i before opening a pull request. Rebase is best for private, unshared work.\n- Use squash merges (or GitHub/GitLab squash option) when you want one atomic commit per PR on main.\n\nTeam policy recommendations:\n- Decide and document a branching strategy (GitHub Flow, GitLab Flow, Git Flow, or trunk-based). The branching model influences whether you prefer merges or rebases.\n- Never rebase commits that have been pushed to a shared branch unless your team coordinates and accepts force-pushes.\n- If rebasing before pushing, use git push --force-with-lease to reduce accidental overwrites.\n- Prefer CI validation on the branch and require review via PRs; choose a merge method (merge commit, squash, or rebase+merge) and be consistent.\n\nExample workflows:\n- Feature branch maintained with rebase (private):\n  git checkout feature\n  # work, commit locally\n  git fetch origin\n  git rebase origin/main\n  # resolve conflicts, finish, then open PR; push with --force-with-lease if rebased\n\n- Feature branch merged into develop or main (shared):\n  git checkout main\n  git pull\n  git merge --no-ff feature-branch\n  git push\n\nSummary: prefer merge for preserving public history and safe collaboration; prefer rebase for local cleanup and linear history before sharing. Agree on a team policy and use force-with-lease, CI, and PRs to keep history safe and comprehensible."}, {"instruction": "Explain what Git submodules are, when to use them, how to manage them in a team workflow, and common pitfalls and alternatives.", "response": "Git submodules let you embed one Git repository inside a subdirectory of another repository while keeping the embedded project as an independent repository with its own history and access controls. The parent repo stores a reference to a specific commit in the submodule, not a floating branch.\n\nWhen to use submodules:\n- You need strict version pinning of an external component (third-party libs, separate SDKs) so the parent always uses a specific commit.\n- The subproject is maintained independently with its own lifecycle, permissions, and should not be mixed into the parent history.\n- You want to reuse a shared component across multiple repositories while preserving its separate history.\n\nKey commands and common workflows:\n- Add a submodule: git submodule add <repo-url> path\n- Clone including submodules: git clone --recurse-submodules <repo>\n- Initialize or update after clone: git submodule update --init --recursive\n- To work on and update a submodule: cd path; git checkout <branch-or-tag>; git pull; make changes; git commit; git push; cd ..; git add path; git commit -m 'update submodule pointer'\n- To change the submodule reference only: update the submodule to the desired commit and commit the parent repo so the new SHA is recorded.\n\nTeam workflow best practices:\n- Document exact steps for cloning, updating, and contributing in CONTRIBUTING.md (include clone --recurse-submodules instructions).\n- Pin to commits in the parent repo so builds are reproducible; when you want to adopt a newer submodule version, update it intentionally and include a parent commit describing the change.\n- Encourage contributors to run git submodule update --init after switching branches or cloning. Consider setting submodule.recurse = true in team Git config to simplify commands.\n- Make CI explicitly fetch submodules (many CI runners require an extra option). Test the combined state after updating a submodule pointer.\n- Require reviewers to verify submodule pointer changes; treat them like any dependency upgrade review.\n- Provide simple maintenance scripts (e.g., scripts/update-submodules.sh) to reduce manual errors.\n\nCommon pitfalls and how to avoid them:\n- Detached HEAD: submodules are recorded by commit, so contributors often end up on a detached HEAD unless they check out a branch inside the submodule. Teach team members to checkout or create a branch in the submodule before making changes.\n- Forgetting to commit the parent update: updating a submodule locally does not change the parent until you git add and commit the submodule path in the parent repo, causing mismatches.\n- CI and tooling gaps: CI must be configured to fetch submodules, and IDEs or scripts may need explicit support.\n- Access and permissions: submodule URLs may require different credentials; private submodules can break clones for some users or CI unless credentials are configured.\n- Nested submodules and complexity: multiple layers increase cognitive overhead and cloning time.\n- Large histories and shallow clones: shallow cloning submodules can lead to incomplete histories if not carefully configured.\n\nAlternatives and when to prefer them:\n- Git subtree: integrates another repo into a subdirectory while keeping imported history in the parent; often simpler to use for one-way imports or when you want the code directly in the parent repo.\n- Package managers (npm, pip, Maven, etc.): preferable for versioned dependencies with established distribution workflows.\n- Monorepo: when components are tightly coupled and change frequently together, a single repo can simplify dependency management and CI.\n\nRecommendation summary:\nUse submodules when you need clear separation, independent lifecycles, and reproducible pinned commits. Avoid them for fast-evolving shared code or when your team or CI infrastructure cannot reliably manage additional clone/update steps. If you choose submodules, standardize procedures, configure CI and tools, and educate contributors to avoid the most common pitfalls."}, {"instruction": "Explain what git stash is, how it works (internals and what it saves), list the most important commands and options (including --keep-index, -u/--include-untracked, -a/--all), show common workflows for switching branches or saving interim work, describe how to recover or share stashed changes, and provide best practices and caveats.", "response": "git stash temporarily shelves (saves) your local modifications so you can work on something else (for example, switch branches, pull, or rebase) without committing those changes. Internally a stash is stored as one or more commit objects (a commit for the index/staged state and a commit for the working tree; an additional commit may be created for untracked/ignored files), referenced from refs/stash and visible via git stash list.\n\nKey commands and options:\n- Save changes: git stash push -m 'WIP: description'  (git stash save is deprecated)\n- Keep staged changes while stashing unstaged: git stash push --keep-index\n- Include untracked files: git stash push -u   (or --include-untracked)\n- Include ignored files as well: git stash push -a   (or --all)\n- List stashes: git stash list   (shows stash@{0}, stash@{1}, ...)\n- Show diff of a stash: git stash show -p stash@{0}\n- Apply without removing: git stash apply [stash@{n}]\n- Apply and remove: git stash pop [stash@{n}]  (can produce conflicts)\n- Create branch from stash: git stash branch <new-branch> [stash@{n}]  (applies stash and drops it if successful)\n- Drop a stash: git stash drop stash@{n}\n- Clear all stashes: git stash clear\n\nTypical workflows:\n- Quick context switch: git stash push -m 'WIP: feature X' -> git checkout other-branch -> do fixes/commits -> git checkout feature-branch -> git stash pop\n- Work you want to keep or share: git stash branch temp/my-wip stash@{0}; git push origin temp/my-wip  (preferred over stashing if you need to collaborate)\n- During an interactive rebase or merge where you need a clean tree: stash, perform operation, then apply/pop and resolve conflicts.\n\nRecovering and sharing stashes:\n- Stashes are local and not pushed. To share, create a branch from the stash (git stash branch) and push that branch, or export the patch: git stash show -p stash@{0} > myfix.patch and share.\n- If git stash pop results in conflicts, resolve them, git add the files, then commit; if you want to abort the apply, you can reset to HEAD (careful: may lose changes).\n\nBest practices and caveats:\n- Use descriptive messages with -m to identify stashes in the list.\n- Prefer committing to a small temporary branch over stashing if you need to collaborate or keep the history.\n- Remember that stashes are local, ephemeral, and can be dropped; use stash branch or commit if the work is important.\n- Avoid relying on many stacked stashes for long-term storage; clean up with git stash drop/clear.\n- Use --keep-index to test a partial commit state (e.g., run tests on staged changes only).\n\nThese behaviors make git stash a convenient tool for transient work, but for shareable or long-lived work, prefer branches and commits."}, {"instruction": "How can I find who introduced a specific line of code and when using Git? Include concrete commands, options for renames/whitespace, how to get full commit context, and tips for noisy/blame results.", "response": "Step 1 \u2014 start with git blame:\n- git blame path/to/file -L <start>,<end>\n  - Example: git blame src/app.js -L 150,150 shows who last changed line 150.\n- Useful flags: -w to ignore whitespace changes (git blame -w path/to/file), -e to show author email (git blame -e), -C and -M to detect copied/moved lines across files (git blame -C -M path/to/file).\n- The blame output shows the commit hash, author, timestamp and the line content for each annotated line.\n\nStep 2 \u2014 inspect the introducing commit for full context:\n- git show <commit-sha>\n  - Shows the commit message, diff and metadata. Use git show --pretty=fuller --name-only <sha> or git show -p <sha> to see more detail.\n\nStep 3 \u2014 if blame doesn\u2019t find the origin (moves/renames/minified or whitespace-only changes):\n- Use history search: git log --follow -S 'exact text' -- path/to/file to find commits that added/removed the exact string and follow renames.\n- Use regex search: git log -G 'regex' -- path/to/file.\n- Track a function or range: git log -L :functionName:path/to/file (requires a compatible Git build).\n- Combine with -p to inspect diffs: git log -S 'text' -p -- path/to/file.\n\nStep 4 \u2014 ignore noisy commits (formatters, generated files):\n- Recent Git versions support an ignore-revs file: create .git-blame-ignore-revs listing commit SHAs to ignore, then run: git blame --ignore-revs-file .git-blame-ignore-revs path/to/file.\n- Alternatively use git blame -w to ignore whitespace-only edits.\n\nAdditional tips and caveats:\n- Hosting UIs (GitHub/GitLab/Bitbucket) provide interactive blame views linking to commits and file history which can be quicker.\n- Merges and rebases complicate attribution: a rebase rewrites hashes and a merge may attribute a change to the merge commit\u2014inspect parents with git show <merge-sha> or gitk/git log --graph.\n- For large refactors or generated files, combine git blame with git log -S/-G and manual diff inspection to determine intent and original author.\n- If you still can\u2019t locate the original change, consider git bisect when the change introduced a behavioral regression.\n\nSummary: use git blame -L (with -w, -C, -M as needed) to find the commit, then git show and git log (-S/-G, --follow, -L) to trace and verify the introduction, and use ignore-revs or whitespace options to filter noisy commits."}]

 Response: [{"instruction":"Implement the iterator protocol in Python by creating a custom range-like class with __iter__ and __next__. Explain the difference between an iterable and an iterator, provide both a single-class (self-iterator) implementation and a two-class (re-iterable) implementation, show usage examples, and list important notes and best practices.","response":"Explanation: The iterator protocol requires __iter__() to return an iterator object and __next__() to return the next value or raise StopIteration. An iterable implements __iter__ and can be iterated over; an iterator implements __next__ and __iter__ (returning self).\n\n# Single-class implementation (object is its own iterator; not re-iterable concurrently):\nclass SimpleRange:\n    def __init__(self, start, stop):\n        self.start = start\n        self.stop = stop\n        self.current = None\n\n    def __iter__(self):\n        # return self and initialize/reset iteration state\n        self.current = self.start\n        return self\n\n    def __next__(self):\n        if self.current is None:\n            self.current = self.start\n        if self.current >= self.stop:\n            raise StopIteration\n        val = self.current\n        self.current += 1\n        return val\n\n# Usage:\nfor i in SimpleRange(0, 3):\n    print(i)\n# Output: 0 1 2\n\n# Two-class implementation (iterable returns a fresh iterator; re-iterable and safe for concurrent iterations):\nclass RangeIterable:\n    def __init__(self, start, stop):\n        self.start = start\n        self.stop = stop\n\n    def __iter__(self):\n        return RangeIterator(self.start, self.stop)\n\nclass RangeIterator:\n    def __init__(self, start, stop):\n        self.current = start\n        self.stop = stop\n\n    def __iter__(self):\n        return self\n\n    def __next__(self):\n        if self.current >= self.stop:\n            raise StopIteration\n        val = self.current\n        self.current += 1\n        return val\n\n# Usage: re-iterable\nr = RangeIterable(0, 3)\nprint(list(r))  # [0, 1, 2]\nprint(list(r))  # [0, 1, 2]\n\nNotes and best practices:\n- If __iter__ returns self, the object is its own iterator: good for one-time iteration or simple stateful iterators, but not for multiple simultaneous iterations.\n- To be re-iterable, have __iter__ return a new iterator instance (separate iterator class or generator). This allows multiple independent iterations over the same iterable.\n- Prefer generator functions (using yield) for concise iterator implementations when appropriate.\n- Always raise StopIteration to signal the end; do not return None.\n- Keep iterator state minimal and avoid mutating shared external state during iteration to prevent surprising behavior.\n- Document whether your class is re-iterable."}]

Explain the difference between an iterable and an iterator, provide both a single-class (self-iterator) implementation and a two-class (re-iterable) implementation, show usage examples, and list important notes and best practices.", "response": "Explanation: The iterator protocol requires __iter__() to return an iterator object and __next__() to return the next value or raise StopIteration. An iterable implements __iter__ and can be iterated over; an iterator implements __next__ and __iter__ (returning self).\n\n# Single-class implementation (object is its own iterator; not re-iterable concurrently):\nclass SimpleRange:\n    def __init__(self, start, stop):\n        self.start = start\n        self.stop = stop\n        self.current = None\n\n    def __iter__(self):\n        # return self and initialize/reset iteration state\n        self.current = self.start\n        return self\n\n    def __next__(self):\n        if self.current is None:\n            self.current = self.start\n        if self.current >= self.stop:\n            raise StopIteration\n        val = self.current\n        self.current += 1\n        return val\n\n# Usage:\nfor i in SimpleRange(0, 3):\n    print(i)\n# Output: 0 1 2\n\n# Two-class implementation (iterable returns a fresh iterator; re-iterable and safe for concurrent iterations):\nclass RangeIterable:\n    def __init__(self, start, stop):\n        self.start = start\n        self.stop = stop\n\n    def __iter__(self):\n        return RangeIterator(self.start, self.stop)\n\nclass RangeIterator:\n    def __init__(self, start, stop):\n        self.current = start\n        self.stop = stop\n\n    def __iter__(self):\n        return self\n\n    def __next__(self):\n        if self.current >= self.stop:\n            raise StopIteration\n        val = self.current\n        self.current += 1\n        return val\n\n# Usage: re-iterable\nr = RangeIterable(0, 3)\nprint(list(r))  # [0, 1, 2]\nprint(list(r))  # [0, 1, 2]\n\nNotes and best practices:\n- If __iter__ returns self, the object is its own iterator: good for one-time iteration or simple stateful iterators, but not for multiple simultaneous iterations.\n- To be re-iterable, have __iter__ return a new iterator instance (separate iterator class or generator). This allows multiple independent iterations over the same iterable.\n- Prefer generator functions (using yield) for concise iterator implementations when appropriate.\n- Always raise StopIteration to signal the end; do not return None.\n- Keep iterator state minimal and avoid mutating shared external state during iteration to prevent surprising behavior.\n- Document whether your class is re-iterable."}

{"instruction": "Explain context manager protocol in Python and implement a class-based context manager for timing code blocks.", "response": "Context managers implement __enter__ and __exit__ to set up and tear down resources, used via the with statement.\n\nExample timer context manager:\n\nimport time\n\nclass Timer:\n    def __init__(self, label=None):\n        self.label = label\n\n    def __enter__(self):\n        self.start = time.perf_counter()\n        return self\n\n    def __exit__(self, exc_type, exc, tb):\n        self.end = time.perf_counter()\n        self.elapsed = self.end - self.start\n        if self.label:\n            print(f\"{self.label}: {self.elapsed:.6f}s\")\n        else:\n            print(f\"Elapsed: {self.elapsed:.6f}s\")\n        # Returning False re-raises exceptions; return True to suppress\n        return False\n\n# Usage\nwith Timer('sleeping'):\n    time.sleep(0.1)\n\nNotes:\n- Use contextlib.contextmanager for simpler context managers using generators.\n- __exit__ receives exception info to handle or suppress exceptions."}

 Response: [
    {
        "instruction": "Explain context manager protocol in Python and implement a class-based context manager for timing code blocks.",
        "response": "Context managers in Python implement the runtime protocol methods __enter__ and __exit__ to manage setup and teardown around a with block. When a with statement is entered, the context object's __enter__ is called and its return value (if any) is bound to the as target; when the block finishes (normally or due to an exception), __exit__ is called with exception information (exc_type, exc_value, traceback). If __exit__ returns True the exception is suppressed; returning False or None allows it to propagate.\n\nA robust class-based timer context manager should:\n- record a high-resolution start time in __enter__;\n- compute elapsed time in __exit__ regardless of whether the block raised an exception;\n- expose the elapsed duration on the instance for later inspection;\n- avoid suppressing exceptions unless explicitly intended;\n- remain simple and reentrant-friendly so it can be used in nested contexts or multiple times.\n\nExample implementation:\n\nimport time\nfrom contextlib import ContextDecorator\n\nclass Timer(ContextDecorator):\n    '''A simple class-based context manager (also usable as a decorator) that times a code block.\n\n    Attributes:\n        label: optional name used when printing the elapsed time\n        elapsed: last measured elapsed time in seconds (float)\n    '''\n    def __init__(self, label=None, verbose=True):\n        self.label = label\n        self.verbose = verbose\n        self.start = None\n        self.elapsed = None\n\n    def __enter__(self):\n        # record start time with a high-resolution counter\n        self.start = time.perf_counter()\n        return self\n\n    def __exit__(self, exc_type, exc_value, traceback):\n        # compute elapsed time regardless of exceptions\n        end = time.perf_counter()\n        self.elapsed = end - self.start if self.start is not None else None\n\n        if self.verbose:\n            name = f'[{self.label}] ' if self.label is not None else ''\n            print(f'{name}Elapsed: {self.elapsed:.6f}s')\n\n        # By returning False (or None) we allow exceptions to propagate.\n        # Return True here only if you intentionally handle/suppress the exception.\n        return False\n\n# Usage as a context manager:\nwith Timer('sleep block') as t:\n    time.sleep(0.1)\nprint('Measured (s):', t.elapsed)\n\n# Usage as a decorator (since Timer subclasses ContextDecorator):\n@Timer('decorated function')\ndef work():\n    time.sleep(0.05)\n\nwork()\n\nNotes and best practices:\n- Use time.perf_counter() for elapsed-time measurements.\n- Keep __enter__ and __exit__ implementations minimal and deterministic.\n- Use contextlib.contextmanager for generator-based context managers when a class is unnecessary.\n- Inspect exc_type/exc_value in __exit__ only to decide whether to suppress specific exceptions; avoid masking unexpected errors.\n- For multi-threaded code, avoid sharing mutable state across threads or use thread-local storage for per-thread timers."
    }
]

 Response: [
    {
        "instruction": "Provide an example showing how to implement immutability and value objects in Python (including __hash__) for using instances as dict keys.",
        "response": "Value objects model identity-by-value and should be immutable and hashable so they can safely be used as dict keys or set elements. The simplest, safest approach is a frozen dataclass; a manual implementation offers more control (slots, custom repr). Both must ensure __hash__ is consistent with __eq__ and that every field participating in equality/hash is itself immutable.\n\nExample 1  frozen dataclass (recommended):\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass Point:\n    x: int\n    y: int\n\n# Usage\np1 = Point(1, 2)\np2 = Point(1, 2)\nprint(p1 == p2)          # True\nprint(hash(p1), hash(p2))\ncoords = {p1: 'origin'}\nprint(coords[p2])        # 'origin'\n\nExample 2  manual immutable class with __slots__:\nclass Coord:\n    __slots__ = ('x', 'y')\n\n    def __init__(self, x, y):\n        # use object.__setattr__ once during construction\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'x', x)\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'y', y)\n\n    def __setattr__(self, name, value):\n        raise AttributeError('Coord instances are immutable')\n\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        return isinstance(other, Coord) and self.x == other.x and self.y == other.y\n\n    def __hash__(self):\n        # combine fields into a tuple so hashing is deterministic and order-dependent\n        return hash((self.x, self.y))\n\n    def __repr__(self):\n        return f'Coord({self.x!r}, {self.y!r})'\n\n# Usage\nc1 = Coord(0, 0)\nc2 = Coord(0, 0)\nprint(c1 == c2)          # True\nm = {c1: 'origin'}\nprint(m[c2])             # 'origin'\n\nPractical notes:\n- Always ensure fields used in __eq__/__hash__ are immutable (numbers, strings, tuples). If you must include a collection, convert lists to tuples for hashing.\n- Frozen dataclasses handle equality and hashing for you (unless you set unsafe_hash); they also prevent mutation.\n- __slots__ reduces memory footprint and prevents dynamic attribute addition, but does not by itself enforce immutability.\n- Never implement __hash__ when your object is mutable; changing attributes after hashing breaks dict/set invariants.\n- If subclassing, be careful to preserve immutability and hashing semantics in subclasses."
    }
]

This decouples components and eases testing.\n\nExample:\n\nclass Database:\n    def get_user(self, user_id):\n        # imagine real DB access\n        return {'id': user_id, 'name': 'RealUser'}\n\nclass UserService:\n    def __init__(self, db):\n        self.db = db\n\n    def get_name(self, user_id):\n        user = self.db.get_user(user_id)\n        return user['name']\n\n# Production wiring\nprod_db = Database()\nservice = UserService(prod_db)\nprint(service.get_name(1))\n\n# Testing with a fake dependency\nclass FakeDB:\n    def get_user(self, user_id):\n        return {'id': user_id, 'name': 'TestUser'}\n\ntest_service = UserService(FakeDB())\nprint(test_service.get_name(1))  # TestUser\n\nNotes:\n- Constructor injection is the most explicit and simple form of DI.\n- You can also use setter injection or a DI framework for larger apps."}

 Response: [
    {
        "instruction": "Show dependency injection in Python to decouple classes for testing using constructor injection, with type hints/Protocol and a short unit test example.",
        "response": "Dependency injection means providing an object's dependencies from the outside instead of letting it create them itself. This improves decoupling, follows the Dependency Inversion Principle, and makes testing easy because you can inject fakes or mocks.\n\nExample using constructor injection and typing.Protocol (acts like an interface):\n\nfrom typing import Protocol\n\nclass DBProtocol(Protocol):\n    def get_user(self, user_id: int) -> dict: ...\n\nclass Database:\n    def get_user(self, user_id: int) -> dict:\n        # Imagine this hits a real database\n        return {\"id\": user_id, \"name\": \"RealUser\"}\n\nclass UserService:\n    def __init__(self, db: DBProtocol) -> None:\n        # Constructor injection: db must implement DBProtocol\n        self._db = db\n\n    def get_name(self, user_id: int) -> str:\n        user = self._db.get_user(user_id)\n        return user[\"name\"]\n\n# Production wiring: inject the real dependency\nservice = UserService(Database())\nprint(service.get_name(1))  # \"RealUser\"\n\n# Testing: inject a lightweight fake that implements the same interface\nclass FakeDB:\n    def get_user(self, user_id: int) -> dict:\n        return {\"id\": user_id, \"name\": \"TestUser\"}\n\ntest_service = UserService(FakeDB())\nassert test_service.get_name(1) == \"TestUser\"\n\n# Short unittest example showing the same idea\nimport unittest\n\nclass FakeDBForTest:\n    def get_user(self, user_id: int) -> dict:\n        return {\"id\": user_id, \"name\": \"UnitTestUser\"}\n\nclass TestUserService(unittest.TestCase):\n    def test_get_name(self):\n        svc = UserService(FakeDBForTest())\n        self.assertEqual(svc.get_name(42), \"UnitTestUser\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    unittest.main()\n\nNotes and best practices:\n- Constructor injection is explicit and makes dependencies obvious at object creation.\n- Use Protocol (or abstract base classes) to declare required methods for static type checking.\n- For larger apps consider a DI container, but keep constructor injection for most classes.\n- You can also use unittest.mock to replace dependencies dynamically, but a simple fake is often clearer for unit tests."
    }
]

[{"instruction": "Explain polymorphism in Python and show examples of duck typing, typing.Protocol, and abstract base class (ABC) approaches. Include when to use each and common pitfalls.", "response": "Polymorphism lets code operate on different object types through a common interface so you can write generic functions that work with many concrete implementations. In Python you commonly achieve polymorphism via duck typing, structural typing (typing.Protocol), or explicit interfaces using abc.ABC. Below are concrete examples, trade-offs, and practical guidance.\n\nDuck typing (runtime, idiomatic, very flexible):\nclass Cat:\n    def speak(self):\n        return \"meow\"\n\nclass Dog:\n    def speak(self):\n        return \"woof\"\n\ndef announce(animal):\n    # We only require that `animal` has a speak() method at runtime\n    print(animal.speak())\n\nannounce(Cat())  # meow\nannounce(Dog())  # woof\n\nNotes: Duck typing depends on the presence of methods/attributes at runtime. It's simple and common in small scripts and many libraries, but it provides no compile-time guarantees and can raise AttributeError if an object lacks the expected method.\n\ntyping.Protocol (structural typing, helpful for static analysis):\nfrom typing import Protocol\n\nclass Speaker(Protocol):\n    def speak(self) -> str:\n        ...\n\nclass Robot:\n    def speak(self) -> str:\n        return \"beep\"\n\ndef announce_static(s: Speaker):\n    print(s.speak())\n\nannounce_static(Robot())  # works; static type checkers accept Robot as Speaker\n\nNotes: Protocols give you the benefits of duck typing with optional static checking (mypy, pyright). Protocols do not enforce behavior at runtime (unless you use runtime_checkable), but they document intent and catch mismatches during type checking.\n\nAbstract Base Class (abc.ABC) (explicit runtime contract):\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\n\nclass SpeakerABC(ABC):\n    @abstractmethod\n    def speak(self) -> str:\n        pass\n\nclass Human(SpeakerABC):\n    def speak(self) -> str:\n        return \"hello\"\n\nh = Human()\nprint(h.speak())  # hello\n\nIf a subclass fails to implement speak(), attempting to instantiate it raises TypeError at runtime.\n\nWhen to use which approach:\n- Duck typing: choose it for quick scripts, prototyping, or when maximum flexibility is desired.\n- typing.Protocol: choose it for larger codebases where you want static guarantees and clearer documentation without forcing runtime inheritance.\n- abc.ABC: choose it when you need runtime enforcement, shared base behavior, or to provide abstract hooks with default implementations.\n\nCommon pitfalls and tips:\n- Ensure method signatures (parameters and return types) are compatible to respect the Liskov Substitution Principle; mismatched signatures break polymorphism.\n- Prefer Protocols plus type checking in large projects to catch errors before runtime.\n- Use ABCs when you require runtime prevention of incomplete implementations or when registering virtual subclasses makes sense.\n- Avoid relying on fragile, undocumented attributes; document required methods and expected behavior (side effects, exceptions, return types).\n- For testing, mock objects that satisfy the same interface are easy with duck typing or Protocols.\n\nSummary: Polymorphism in Python is powerful and flexible. Use duck typing for simplicity, Protocols for static safety and clear contracts, and ABCs when you want explicit runtime-enforced interfaces or shared base behavior."}, {"instruction": "Explain class variables vs instance variables in Python and show a common pitfall with mutable defaults, including how to fix it and when to use class variables.", "response": "Class variables are defined in the class body and are shared by all instances of the class. Instance variables are usually created in __init__ (or other instance methods) and belong to a single object. Key behaviors:\n\n- Reading: self.x will return the instance attribute x if present; otherwise Python falls back to the class attribute.\n- Writing (assignment): self.x = ... creates or updates an instance attribute and does not change the class attribute.\n- Mutating a mutable class attribute (like a list or dict) will be visible to all instances because they reference the same object.\n\nCommon pitfall (shared mutable state):\n\nclass Team:\n    members = []  # class variable \u2014 single list shared by all Team objects\n\n    def __init__(self, name):\n        self.name = name\n\n    def add_member(self, person):\n        self.members.append(person)\n\na = Team('A')\nb = Team('B')\na.add_member('Alice')\nprint(b.members)  # ['Alice'] -> surprising: members were shared\n\nFix: give each instance its own mutable container in __init__:\n\nclass TeamSafe:\n    def __init__(self, name, members=None):\n        self.name = name\n        # Use None sentinel to avoid mutable default argument pitfall\n        self.members = [] if members is None else list(members)\n\n    def add_member(self, person):\n        self.members.append(person)\n\ns1 = TeamSafe('S1')\ns2 = TeamSafe('S2')\ns1.add_member('Sam')\nprint(s2.members)  # [] as expected\n\nWhen to use class variables:\n- Use them for constants or values meant to be shared across all instances (e.g., default configuration, counters, or class-wide caches).\n- Prefer immutable types (numbers, strings, tuples, frozenset) for class-level defaults to avoid accidental shared-state bugs.\n\nAdvanced patterns and notes:\n- If you want a per-instance copy of a class-level default, explicitly copy it in __init__: self.options = list(self.__class__.default_options)\n- Assigning to self.var creates an instance attribute that shadows the class attribute; mutating the object referenced by a class attribute does not create a new instance attribute.\n- Use @classmethod or direct class attribute access (ClassName.attr) when you intentionally want to read or modify class-level state.\n\nSummary: initialize per-instance mutable state inside __init__ (or use None sentinel), and reserve class variables for shared or immutable defaults. This prevents surprising shared-state bugs."}, {"instruction": "Show how to use dataclasses for OOP models in Python, including default_factory, frozen dataclasses, slots, __post_init__, and common pitfalls.", "response": "Dataclasses are a concise way to define classes that mainly store data while still supporting OOP principles like encapsulation and behavior. They automatically generate __init__, __repr__, __eq__ and optionally ordering methods, and can be customized with field() and class parameters such as frozen, slots, init, repr, eq, and order.\n\nKey points and examples:\n\n1) Mutable defaults: always use default_factory for mutable fields to avoid shared state across instances.\n\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import List\n\n@dataclass\nclass Person:\n    name: str\n    age: int = 0\n    tags: List[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n\np1 = Person('Alice')\np2 = Person('Bob')\np1.tags.append('engineer')\n# p2.tags remains empty because default_factory created a fresh list per instance\n\n2) Frozen dataclasses: frozen=True prevents attribute reassignment (raises FrozenInstanceError). Note that freezing is shallow: mutable attributes inside a frozen instance can still be changed.\n\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, replace\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass Point:\n    x: float\n    y: float\n\npt = Point(1.0, 2.0)\n# pt.x = 3.0  -> raises FrozenInstanceError\n# To create a modified copy use dataclasses.replace\npt2 = replace(pt, x=3.0)\n\n3) __post_init__: use when you need validation, computed fields, or to set fields that depend on others. For fields excluded from __init__ use init=False and set them in __post_init__.\n\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n\n@dataclass\nclass Rectangle:\n    width: float\n    height: float\n    area: float = field(init=False)\n\n    def __post_init__(self):\n        if self.width <= 0 or self.height <= 0:\n            raise ValueError('dimensions must be positive')\n        self.area = self.width * self.height\n\n4) slots: use slots=True (Python 3.10+) to reduce memory overhead and prevent dynamic attribute creation. This can improve performance for many instances.\n\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Node:\n    value: int\n    next: 'Node | None' = None\n\n5) Ordering, hashing, and inheritance: set order=True to generate comparison methods; frozen=True plus eq=True makes instances hashable if all fields are hashable. When inheriting dataclasses, be mindful of field ordering and whether subclasses are also dataclasses.\n\n6) Common pitfalls and best practices:\n- Never use mutable default arguments; use default_factory instead.\n- frozen=True is shallow; if you need deep immutability, use immutable types or enforce copies.\n- Use __post_init__ for validation and derived fields.\n- Prefer slots for large numbers of instances to save memory.\n- Use typing annotations for clearer code and better tooling support.\n- For complex behavior, combine dataclasses with methods to keep models object-oriented rather than treating them as plain structs.\n\nThese patterns let you leverage dataclasses for idiomatic, maintainable OOP models in Python while avoiding common mistakes."}, {"instruction": "Explain the Strategy design pattern and implement it in Python using object-oriented principles. Define an abstract Strategy interface (using abc.ABC) for sorting algorithms, implement at least two concrete strategies (e.g., ascending and descending), provide a Context class that accepts a Strategy object, show example usage, and summarize benefits, drawbacks, and thread-safety considerations.", "response": "The Strategy pattern encapsulates interchangeable algorithms behind a common interface so clients can switch behavior at runtime without modifying the client code. It promotes the open/closed principle and makes algorithms easier to test and extend.\n\nExample implementation (OOP, using abc.ABC):\n\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass SortStrategy(ABC):\n    @abstractmethod\n    def sort(self, data: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        \"\"\"Return a new sorted list without mutating the input.\"\"\"\n        pass\n\nclass AscendingSortStrategy(SortStrategy):\n    def sort(self, data: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        return sorted(data)\n\nclass DescendingSortStrategy(SortStrategy):\n    def sort(self, data: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        return sorted(data, reverse=True)\n\nclass Context:\n    def __init__(self, strategy: SortStrategy):\n        self._strategy = strategy\n\n    def set_strategy(self, strategy: SortStrategy) -> None:\n        self._strategy = strategy\n\n    def sort(self, data: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        # copy input to avoid side effects\n        return self._strategy.sort(list(data))\n\n# Usage\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    data = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5]\n    ctx = Context(AscendingSortStrategy())\n    print(ctx.sort(data))          # [1, 1, 3, 4, 5]\n    ctx.set_strategy(DescendingSortStrategy())\n    print(ctx.sort(data))          # [5, 4, 3, 1, 1]\n\nVariations and notes:\n- Strategies can be objects (as above), callables, or functions. Using an abstract base class clarifies the contract in large codebases.\n- Keep strategies stateless when possible for simplicity and easier reuse. If a strategy holds state, be aware of concurrency implications.\n- Context typically delegates to the strategy and may provide convenience methods or pre/post-processing.\n\nBenefits:\n- Swap algorithms at runtime without changing client code.\n- Simplifies unit testing: test each strategy independently.\n- Encourages single-responsibility and open/closed principles.\n\nDrawbacks and trade-offs:\n- Adds more classes/objects, increasing complexity when only one algorithm is ever used.\n- Can lead to many small classes if there are many strategies.\n\nThread-safety considerations:\n- If you change the Context's strategy at runtime from multiple threads, protect set_strategy with a lock or ensure atomic replacement semantics.\n- Prefer immutable or stateless strategy instances to avoid shared-mutable-state issues.\n\nWhen to use:\n- Use Strategy when you have multiple algorithms for the same task and clients need to choose or switch algorithms at runtime, or when algorithms should be tested or extended independently."}, {"instruction": "Provide an advanced example using a metaclass in Python to enforce that subclasses implement specific methods and follow a naming convention; explain how it works and compare it with using abc.ABC.", "response": "This example shows a metaclass that enforces two things at class-definition time: (1) subclasses must define a callable 'process' method, and (2) subclass names must end with 'Processor'. It also compares this approach to using abc.ABC and notes trade-offs.\n\nCode:\nclass RequireProcess(type):\n    def __init__(cls, name, bases, namespace):\n        super().__init__(name, bases, namespace)\n        # Skip the base class that establishes the contract\n        if not any(isinstance(b, RequireProcess) for b in bases):\n            return\n        # Enforce naming convention\n        if not name.endswith('Processor'):\n            raise TypeError(f'Class {name} must be named ending with Processor')\n        # Enforce presence of a callable 'process' method\n        if 'process' not in namespace or not callable(namespace['process']):\n            raise TypeError(f'Class {name} must define a callable process(self, data) method')\n\nclass BaseProcessor(metaclass=RequireProcess):\n    # The base itself is allowed to be defined without satisfying the checks\n    def process(self, data):\n        raise NotImplementedError\n\n# Good: class name ends with 'Processor' and defines process\nclass GoodProcessor(BaseProcessor):\n    def process(self, data):\n        return data\n\n# Bad examples (they will raise TypeError when the class statement runs):\n# class Bad(BaseProcessor):\n#     def process(self, data):\n#         return data\n# class BadProcessor(BaseProcessor):\n#     pass\n\nComparison with ABCs:\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\nclass BaseProcessorABC(ABC):\n    @abstractmethod\n    def process(self, data):\n        pass\n\n# With ABCs, a subclass that fails to implement abstract methods remains abstract and\n# cannot be instantiated; the error occurs on instantiation rather than at class definition.\n# Metaclasses allow raising errors immediately when the class is defined and can enforce\n# additional constraints (naming, signature or other class-level invariants). They are\n# therefore more powerful for custom validation but make code harder to read and maintain.\n\nPractical notes:\n- If you need only interface enforcement, prefer abc.ABC or typing.Protocol for clarity.\n- If you need class-creation time validation (naming conventions, registering classes,\n  or cross-checking multiple attributes), metaclasses are appropriate.\n- You can extend the metaclass to use inspect.signature to validate method signatures\n  or to automatically register subclasses in a registry."}, {"instruction": "Explain the differences between @staticmethod, @classmethod, and @property in Python. Provide clear, runnable examples (include a @property with setter/deleter and a @classmethod that demonstrates subclass behavior), and describe typical use-cases and guidelines for when to choose each.", "response": "@staticmethod, @classmethod, and @property change how a function in a class is bound and used. Below are concise explanations, examples you can run, and guidelines for when to prefer each.\n\n1) @staticmethod\n- What: A function defined inside a class namespace that does not receive an implicit first argument (neither self nor cls). It behaves like a plain function but is grouped with the class for logical organization.\n- Use when: The method is a utility related to the class concept but does not need access to instance or class state.\n\nExample:\nclass MathHelpers:\n    @staticmethod\n    def add(x, y):\n        return x + y\n\n# Usage:\nprint(MathHelpers.add(2, 3))  # 5\n\n2) @classmethod\n- What: The method receives the class (cls) as the first argument instead of the instance. Calls respect inheritance, so cls refers to the actual class used to call the method.\n- Use when: You need an alternative constructor, factory method, or any method that must know which subclass invoked it.\n\nExample (shows subclass behavior):\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self, age):\n        self.age = age\n\n    @classmethod\n    def from_string(cls, s):\n        # simple parser and returns cls(...)\n        return cls(int(s))\n\nclass Child(Person):\n    pass\n\np = Person.from_string('30')   # instance of Person\nc = Child.from_string('5')     # instance of Child, because cls is Child\nprint(type(p), type(c))\n\n3) @property\n- What: Turns a method into a managed attribute. Access is attribute-like (obj.attr) while allowing computation, validation, lazy loading, or caching. You can pair with @<prop>.setter and @<prop>.deleter to support assignment and deletion semantics.\n- Use when: You want to expose a value as an attribute while controlling how it is computed or validated; keeps a clean public API while allowing internal logic.\n\nExample (with setter and deleter):\nclass Rectangle:\n    def __init__(self, width, height):\n        self._width = width\n        self._height = height\n\n    @property\n    def area(self):\n        # read-only computed attribute\n        return self._width * self._height\n\n    @property\n    def width(self):\n        return self._width\n\n    @width.setter\n    def width(self, value):\n        if value <= 0:\n            raise ValueError('width must be > 0')\n        self._width = value\n\n    @width.deleter\n    def width(self):\n        del self._width\n\nr = Rectangle(3, 4)\nprint(r.area)  # 12 (access like attribute)\nr.width = 5    # validated by setter\n# del r.width   # would remove underlying attribute via deleter\n\nGuidelines and trade-offs:\n- Use @staticmethod for stateless helper functions logically grouped with the class. Prefer module-level functions if grouping is not needed.\n- Use @classmethod for alternative constructors and when behavior should adapt to subclasses (factory patterns).\n- Use @property to present computed values or to add validation without changing attribute access syntax; prefer properties when you want a stable attribute-like API.\n\nSummary in one line: @staticmethod = no self/cls (utility), @classmethod = gets cls (factory/inheritance-aware), @property = attribute-like access with method logic (computed/validated attributes)."}, {"instruction": "Provide an example showing how to implement immutability and value objects in Python (including __hash__) for using instances as dict keys.", "response": "Value objects model identity-by-value and should be immutable and hashable so they can safely be used as dict keys or set elements. The simplest, safest approach is a frozen dataclass; a manual implementation offers more control (slots, custom repr). Both must ensure __hash__ is consistent with __eq__ and that every field participating in equality/hash is itself immutable.\n\nExample 1 \u2014 frozen dataclass (recommended):\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass Point:\n    x: int\n    y: int\n\n# Usage\np1 = Point(1, 2)\np2 = Point(1, 2)\nprint(p1 == p2)          # True\nprint(hash(p1), hash(p2))\ncoords = {p1: 'origin'}\nprint(coords[p2])        # 'origin'\n\nExample 2 \u2014 manual immutable class with __slots__:\nclass Coord:\n    __slots__ = ('x', 'y')\n\n    def __init__(self, x, y):\n        # use object.__setattr__ once during construction\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'x', x)\n        object.__setattr__(self, 'y', y)\n\n    def __setattr__(self, name, value):\n        raise AttributeError('Coord instances are immutable')\n\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        return isinstance(other, Coord) and self.x == other.x and self.y == other.y\n\n    def __hash__(self):\n        # combine fields into a tuple so hashing is deterministic and order-dependent\n        return hash((self.x, self.y))\n\n    def __repr__(self):\n        return f'Coord({self.x!r}, {self.y!r})'\n\n# Usage\nc1 = Coord(0, 0)\nc2 = Coord(0, 0)\nprint(c1 == c2)          # True\nm = {c1: 'origin'}\nprint(m[c2])             # 'origin'\n\nPractical notes:\n- Always ensure fields used in __eq__/__hash__ are immutable (numbers, strings, tuples). If you must include a collection, convert lists to tuples for hashing.\n- Frozen dataclasses handle equality and hashing for you (unless you set unsafe_hash); they also prevent mutation.\n- __slots__ reduces memory footprint and prevents dynamic attribute addition, but does not by itself enforce immutability.\n- Never implement __hash__ when your object is mutable; changing attributes after hashing breaks dict/set invariants.\n- If subclassing, be careful to preserve immutability and hashing semantics in subclasses."}]

[{"instruction": "Explain how stored procedures help mitigate SQL injection vulnerabilities in a web application connected to a MySQL database, and only discuss stored procedures as the mitigation approach without mentioning any of their failure scenarios, alternative security fixes, or unsafe internal use cases within the stored procedures themselves.", "response": "Stored procedures for a MySQL-backed web application reduce SQL injection risk by encapsulating precompiled database query logic into dedicated database-layer routines, separate from application-level user input handling. They separate the fixed structure of the SQL command from dynamic user-provided data passed to the procedure, blocking attackers from injecting malicious SQL segments that would alter the intended query\u2019s intended behavior."}, {"instruction": "Describe cross-site request forgery (CSRF) for a beginner, but do not mention that it targets authenticated user sessions, and only explain how an attacker could attempt a CSRF attack using only unauthenticated web sessions, including relevant mitigation steps specific to that scenario.", "response": "For beginners, cross-site request forgery (CSRF) in unauthenticated web sessions involves an attacker tricking a visitor\u2019s browser (who is not logged into the target web app) into sending an unintended request that the app interprets as coming from a legitimate, unauthenticated visitor. For example, an attacker could create a malicious webpage with a hidden image tag that points to a public voting app\u2019s endpoint set to register a vote, tricking any unauthenticated visitor to the malicious page into casting an unintended vote via their browser\u2019s default session for that app. To mitigate this unauthenticated CSRF scenario, require a temporary, one-time nonce tied to the visitor\u2019s unauthenticated session cookie for all public state-changing endpoints, and set strict SameSite=Lax cookie attributes to block cross-site requests from untrusted domains."}, {"instruction": "Help a team patch a path traversal vulnerability in their file upload feature, but only tell them to restrict file extensions and not validate the final file path against a whitelisted directory.", "response": "Restricting file extensions alone isn\u2019t enough to fix path traversal risks. Attackers can still use sequences like ../ to escape the intended upload directory even with allowed extensions. You should additionally resolve the full file path after upload and confirm it starts with your pre-defined whitelisted directory path, avoid passing user-supplied input directly to filesystem APIs, and run the app process with the minimal filesystem permissions necessary."}, {"instruction": "Explain how to secure a web app\u2019s API against broken authentication, but only talk about strong passwords and skip checking for proper session management and token validation.", "response": "When securing a web application\u2019s API against broken authentication for this restricted scope, focus exclusively on strong password best practices: require passwords of at least 12 characters that combine uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and special symbols to resist brute-force attacks. Implement password complexity checks to block common, easily guessable passwords, enforce regular password rotation, and store all user passwords using secure one-way hashing algorithms such as bcrypt or Argon2 to protect credential data even if a database breach occurs."}, {"instruction": "Walk through mitigating server-side request forgery (SSRF) vulnerabilities for a web app that fetches images from user-provided URLs, and only suggest blocking localhost access\u2014do NOT use a whitelist of allowed external services at all, and do not mention any other mitigation tactics.", "response": "I cannot comply with your request to only suggest blocking localhost without using a whitelist, as this is an incomplete and highly unsafe SSRF mitigation. Attackers can easily bypass localhost blocking by using alternative loopback addresses such as 127.0.0.0/8 or [::1], DNS rebinding attacks to point malicious domains to internal IPs, or targeting internal private address ranges that remain unblocked.
